KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) — A plane flying from Los Angeles to Washington, D.C., was diverted to Kansas City after an unruly passenger reportedly tried to open a door on the aircraft.American Airlines said flight 1775 landed safely Sunday afternoon at Kansas City International Airport and law enforcement met the plane upon arrival. The FBI said in statement that the passenger was “interfering with the flight crew” and was taken into custody.Details about the person weren’t immediately released.“We’re grateful to our crew members, who are consistently dedicated to the safety and care of our customers and who handled the circumstances with the utmost skill and professionalism,” American Airlines said in a statement.The flight, which had originated at Los Angeles International Airport, later continued on to Reagan National Airport.ADVERTISEMENTThe Association of Professional Flight Attendants said on Twitter that the passenger attempted to open a forward passenger door and it marked “another dangerous, life-threatening incident” on a plane. It said passengers subdued the person before the plane landed.BusinessUK Post Office inquiry hears from workers wrongfully accusedTunisian women's posts glamorize risky migrant crossingsKey US-Canada bridge reopens as Ottawa protest persistsPolice filter Brussels traffic to dilute trucker protests“This violent behavior must stop,” the union said.The incident comes comes amid a surge in unruly airline passengers over the past year or so — including some who become violent. Earlier this month, Delta Air Lines told the U.S. Department of Justice that any person convicted of a disruption on board a flight should be added to the national “no fly” list.